# Documentation rules (express-mongoose)

## README expectations (when updating)
- Keep it focused on getting the app running locally:
  - Prereqs: Node.js + MongoDB
  - Install: `npm install`
  - Run: `npm start` (nodemon) and `npm run start-server` (node)
  - Env vars: `MONGODB_URI` (and recommend `SESSION_SECRET` if/when added)
- Mention main features:
  - EJS SSR pages
  - sessions stored in MongoDB
  - CSRF protection
  - login/signup/logout
  - products/cart/orders/admin
- Include a short route overview (public vs authenticated).
- Avoid claiming API formats like OpenAPI unless the repo actually contains them (it doesn’t).

## Inline code comments
- Prefer minimal comments; document “why”, not “what”.
- If adding non-obvious middleware ordering (sessions → csrf → flash), add a short comment explaining dependency/order.

## File-level docs (when adding new modules)
- Put new Express middleware in `middleware/`.
- Put new model logic in `models/` and keep controllers free of persistence details where possible.
- Put helper utilities in `util/`.

## Examples
- Any code snippet in docs should match the repo’s current style:
  - CommonJS (`require`, `module.exports`)
  - Promise chains (unless the codebase is being refactored consistently to async/await)